			p(lang='en') Methane (play /ˈmɛθeɪn/) is a chemical compound with the chemical formula CH<sub>4</sub>. It is the simplest alkane, and the principal component of natural gas. Methane's bond angles are 109.5 degrees. Burning methane in the presence of oxygen produces carbon dioxide and water. The relative abundance of methane makes it an attractive fuel. However, because it is a gas at normal temperature and pressure, methane is difficult to transport from its source. It is generally transported in bulk by pipeline in its natural gas form, or <abbr title="Liquified Natural Gas">LNG</abbr> carriers in its liquefied form; few countries transport it by truck.